His baseball career spanned nine seasons, four of which were spent in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) with the [[Seattle Mariners]] (1977–1980), and the [[California Angels]] (1983). McLaughlin, a right-handed [[pitcher]] used primarily in [[relief pitcher|relief]], compiled a major league [[Win–loss record (pitching)|record]] of 16–25 with a 5.11 [[earned run average]], five [[complete games]], 16 [[save (baseball)|saves]], and 74 [[strikeouts]] in 378{{frac|1|3}} [[innings pitched]].


After his career, McLaughlin allegedly worked in the counterfeit consumer goods industry in [[Mexico]] making [[Dupes|knock-off]] athletic [[footwear]], which included shoes designed to look like [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]], [[Vans]], and [[Adidas]]. In October 1984, a [[Warrant (law)|warrant]] was issued for McLaughlin's arrest after he failed to appear in court on previous charges.<ref>{{Cite news |date=1984-10-14 |title=Davis, Hurt at Forum, Out at Least 6 Weeks |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/the-los-angeles-times-davis-hurt-at-for/163514127/ |access-date=2025-01-20 |work=The Los Angeles Times |page=III-15 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> McLaughlin was arrested for illegally trafficking [[counterfeit consumer goods|counterfeit shoes]] and [[money laundering]] in 1990.<ref name="counterfeit">{{cite magazine|last=MacFarquhar|first=Larissa|title=Bag Man|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2007/03/19/070319fa_fact_macfarquhar|magazine=The New Yorker|access-date=November 24, 2010|date=March 19, 2007}}</ref> According to ''[[The New Yorker]]'', McLaughlin, who had ties in Mexico from when he played baseball there, made deals with [[Korea]]n businesspeople to make counterfeit footwear. The brands that he counterfeited included [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]], [[Vans]], and [[Adidas]], which he manufactured to sell in the Mexican market. Harley Lewin, a lawyer who pursued people in the counterfeit business, found that McLaughlin was making 80,000 pairs of sneakers for about $750,000 any given month.<ref name=counterfeit /> At the time of the investigation, McLaughlin had a secret account in Luxembourg with $2.4 million.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Court rejects beyond-borders case|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1995/10/02/Court-rejects-beyond-borders-case/5460812606400/|access-date=2020-07-23|website=UPI|language=en}}</ref>
In 1986, McLaughlin started a new career as a general import and export clerk for a small company in San Diego, California. He consulted with a trademark attorney in San Diego, California who advised him about grey market shoes, shipped from Korea to Mexico without coming on to US territory.


Lewin also discovered that half of all counterfeit footwear in Mexico could be traced back to McLaughlin's business. McLaughlin pleaded guilty to the money laundering charges, but fled the country before being sentenced. While it is believed he has been living near [[Cannes]] in [[France]] for years, he has moved from that spot and his whereabouts are now unknown as he is a fugitive from justice.<ref name="counterfeit" />
McLaughlin was arrested in December 1989 by the US Attorney’s office for trafficking in counterfeit goods and causing a fraudulent transport manifest entry document to be used involving 40 cartons of Vans sport shoes (400 pairs). U.S. Customs seized them at the Nogales border crossing on August 4th, 1989. The total value was USD 4,900.00 (four thousand nine hundred ninety dollars).<ref>{{Cite web |title=About – Byron McLaughlin |url=https://byronmcl.com/about/ |access-date=2026-02-10 |language=en-US}}</ref>

His case finally got resolved in 2012. All charges against Mr. McLaughlin were dismissed by the US District Court in Tucson, Arizona. Today, McLaughlin lives in HCMC, Vietnam, and holds a 10-year validity United States passport by the U.S. Embassy.
